The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Triveni to pump in Rs 650 cr for growth

 GARIMA SINGH

 New Delhi, May 28: Triveni Engineering and Industries Limited (TEIL) will invest about Rs 650 crore this fiscal to expand its sugar and engineering businesses.

 We have earmarked approximately Rs 650 crore to expand both lines of our business, said Dhruv M. Sawhney, chairman and managing director of TEIL.

 According to him, the company will invest in setting up three new sugar factories in Chandanpur, Raninangal and Swar in Uttar Pradesh. 

 TEIL has four sugar mills at Ramkola, Sabitgarh, Khatauli and Deoband in UP.

 According to Tarun Sawhney, corporate vice-president of TEIL, the Ramkola mills capacity will be increased by 3,000 tonnes crushing per day (TCD). This will take the total sugarcane crushing capacity to 6,500 TCD from 3,500 at present. While the capacity at Chandanpur and Swar mills will be 6,000 TCD each, that of Raninangal mill will be 5,500 TCD.

 The mill at Swar will be operational by January next year and the remaining two will start in the next sugar season, which is usually in October, November, said Tarun. 

 Moreover, the company is increasing its number of rural retail stores, Triveni Khushali Bazaar, from 11 to 45 by next year.

 TEIL will expand its turbine plant in Bangalore at an investment of Rs 45 crore.

 It will also set up a 160-kl distillery to produce alcohol from sugarcane. 

 Triveni reported a 32 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 39.8 crore on a revenue of Rs 341.9 crore for the fourth quarter ended March 31.

 In 2005-06, net revenue grew 24 per cent at Rs 1,192 crore against Rs 961 crore in the previous fiscal.

 Consolidated net revenue of the Triveni group for 2005-06 stood at Rs 1,192 crore against Rs 964.9 crore in the previous fiscal.




